Diagnosis.
Large species with elongated and pointed opisthosoma, distinguished from southern African congeners by the shape of the bulb (no pointed projection, shape of apophysis; 
Fig. 252
), and by the wide distance between the long male cheliceral apophyses (
Fig. 254
).

Diagnosis.
Medium size species with oval opisthosoma, distinguished from southern African congeners by the shapes of the bulb (single projection, 
Fig. 257
), the procursus (
Figs 257, 258
), and the male cheliceral apophyses (
Fig. 256
). The ZFMK has a very close relative from Signal Hill, 
Cape
Town, with minimally different procursus but with the male cheliceral apophyses much wider apart (distance between tips: 150 Mm).
